00:47:23.540 --> 00:47:25.810
I'm so moved.

00:47:25.810 --> 00:47:31.020
I am so moved to think that after
so, so many years we are going

00:47:31.020 --> 00:47:32.820
to see peace in our lifetime.

00:47:32.820 --> 00:47:36.590
That is the most exciting
thing I can think of.

00:47:36.590 --> 00:47:42.590
And I truly hope that all of us
Colombians will be able to see

00:47:42.590 --> 00:47:43.960
that in some kind of way.

00:47:43.960 --> 00:47:45.810
Is this peace treaty perfect?

00:47:45.810 --> 00:47:48.150
No, but no peace is
going to be perfect.

00:47:48.150 --> 00:47:53.510 position:56%
It's -- there's been so much pain
and so many violations of everything

00:47:53.510 --> 00:47:56.400
that it's impossible
to think of a way

00:47:56.400 --> 00:48:01.990
that would erase the
problematic entirely, but I truly,

00:48:01.990 --> 00:48:05.640
truly hope for a yes and that
people will see the value

00:48:05.640 --> 00:48:08.880
of what has been done in
Cuba in all the talks.

00:48:08.880 --> 00:48:10.180
Yeah. Yeah.

00:48:10.180 --> 00:48:11.480
Yes?

00:48:11.480 --> 00:48:17.620
&gt;&gt; How much of a culture
shock was [inaudible]?

00:48:17.620 --> 00:48:19.980
&gt;&gt; Juana Medina: Oh,
it was interesting

00:48:19.980 --> 00:48:25.750
because my grandparents lived in
Boston for a while, so I had grown

00:48:25.750 --> 00:48:29.830
up hearing a lot of stories about
Boston and I -- we had visited.

00:48:29.830 --> 00:48:32.830
So it wasn't a tremendous shock,

00:48:32.830 --> 00:48:35.620
until conversations
started to come forward.

00:48:35.620 --> 00:48:39.840
I remember in particular talking
to somebody for about half an hour

00:48:39.840 --> 00:48:41.850
and she must have been
completely absent-minded and all

00:48:41.850 --> 00:48:44.100
of a sudden she turns to
me and she says, you know,

00:48:44.100 --> 00:48:47.940
I just realized this is the first
person, I talked to a brown person.

00:48:47.940 --> 00:48:54.330
And I couldn't even
think of what to say.

00:48:54.330 --> 00:48:58.410
So, yeah, there have
been interesting things,

00:48:58.410 --> 00:49:01.080
but not all of them have
happened in New England.

00:49:01.080 --> 00:49:02.380
I love New England.

00:49:02.380 --> 00:49:06.350
I'll be there in a week
or so, and I love it.

00:49:06.350 --> 00:49:08.140
But it was interesting.

00:49:08.140 --> 00:49:11.560
D.C. also has -- I mean, I
remember I was volunteering

00:49:11.560 --> 00:49:13.580
at Walter Reed Army Medical Center,

00:49:13.580 --> 00:49:17.490
and on my first day this very
kind woman was guiding me

00:49:17.490 --> 00:49:20.430 position:56%
through the hospital, which is huge.

00:49:20.430 --> 00:49:22.960
This was at the prior location.

00:49:22.960 --> 00:49:24.930
And all of a sudden
she said, wait hold on,

00:49:24.930 --> 00:49:26.710
I need to show you something,

00:49:26.710 --> 00:49:29.950
because I had told
her I was Colombian

00:49:29.950 --> 00:49:31.800
and I had just arrived
and all these things.

00:49:31.800 --> 00:49:36.670
And she said, let me show
you, this is an elevator.

00:49:36.670 --> 00:49:39.230
If you press this button you go up.

00:49:39.230 --> 00:49:40.900
If you press this button
you go down.

00:49:40.900 --> 00:49:45.420
And I was like, wow, you know, we
don't have those in the jungle.

00:49:45.420 --> 00:49:48.030
I mean, it's just like, oh my God.

00:49:48.030 --> 00:49:53.570
I mean, how do you
even -- so I just said,

00:49:53.570 --> 00:49:55.070
thank you, thank you very much.

00:49:55.070 --> 00:49:59.570
And then later on --
because I think people most

00:49:59.570 --> 00:50:01.360
of the time do it out of kindness.

00:50:01.360 --> 00:50:04.470
And there's some nervousness
and simply not knowing.

00:50:04.470 --> 00:50:09.010
And I'm sure I have said
awful, awful things to people,

00:50:09.010 --> 00:50:10.790
you know, in many situations.

00:50:10.790 --> 00:50:12.860
So it was hard.

00:50:12.860 --> 00:50:17.440
At the end of the, you know, just a
few minutes later we were standing

00:50:17.440 --> 00:50:20.080
in line and she said, so
how is the cultural shock?

00:50:20.080 --> 00:50:22.770
You know, how hard has it
been to adapt to the city?

00:50:22.770 --> 00:50:25.340
And I said, you know, I feel
like I'm in a small town.

00:50:25.340 --> 00:50:28.160
It feels so tiny and the
buildings are so short.

00:50:28.160 --> 00:50:30.150
And she was like, really?

00:50:30.150 --> 00:50:38.880
Really? So, yeah, I think, again,
kindness goes a long way, yeah.

